1. Bubble Sort (MOST COMMON)
Idea (Simple)

Compare adjacent elements

Swap if order is wrong

Largest element moves to the end in each pass



public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        int[] arr = {5, 1, 4, 2, 8};
        int n = arr.length;

        int swapCount = 0;     // Step 1: total swaps count

        // Step 2: Outer loop → number of passes
        for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {

            boolean swapped = false;  // Step 3: check if any swap happens in this pass

            // Step 4: Inner loop → compare adjacent elements
            for (int j = 0; j < n - 1 - i; j++) {

                // Step 5: If left element is bigger → swap
                if (arr[j] > arr[j + 1]) {

                    int temp = arr[j];
                    arr[j] = arr[j + 1];
                    arr[j + 1] = temp;

                    swapCount++;      // Step 6: increase swap count
                    swapped = true;   // Step 7: mark that swap happened
                }
            }

            // Step 8: If no swap in this pass → already sorted
            if (!swapped) {
                break;
            }
        }

        // Step 9: Print sorted array
        System.out.print("Sorted Array: ");
        for (int x : arr) {
            System.out.print(x + " ");
        }

Time Complexity

Best: O(n)

Average/Worst: O(n²)

Interview Q

Q: Why bubble sort is slow?
A: Because it compares elements repeatedly using nested loops.
        // Step 10: Print total swaps
        System.out.println("\nTotal Swaps: " + swapCount);
    }
}
